  "Diffuse reflection occurs when light hits a rough surface and scatters in many directions. This is why rough surfaces like paper do not produce clear mirror images, unlike smooth surfaces that produce specular reflection.": "",
  "When light leaves a denser medium and enters a less dense medium, it bends:": "",
  "Toward the surface boundary": "",
  "Away from the normal line": "",
  "Toward the normal line": "",
  "It does not bend at all": "",
  "When light travels from a denser medium (higher n) to a less dense medium (lower n), it bends away from the normal. This is the opposite of what happens when entering a denser medium.": "",
  "What is the normal in the context of reflection and refraction?": "",
  "A line drawn parallel to the reflecting surface at the point of incidence": "",
  "A line drawn perpendicular to the surface at the point where light hits": "",
  "The average direction of the reflected and refracted rays combined": "",
  "A line that runs along the boundary between the two different media": "",
  "The normal is an imaginary line drawn perpendicular (at 90°) to the surface at the point where light strikes. All angles in reflection and refraction are measured from this normal line.": "",
