  "Define the term 'refraction' in physics.": "",
  "The bouncing of light off a surface back into the same medium": "",
  "The bending of light as it passes from one medium to another": "",
  "The splitting of white light into its component color spectrum": "",
  "The absorption of light energy by a material's surface atoms": "",
  "Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one medium to another due to a change in speed. The amount of bending depends on the refractive indices of the two media involved.": "",
  "What does the term 'medium' mean in optics?": "",
  "The material or substance through which light travels": "",
  "The midpoint between a light source and a detector": "",
  "The average speed of light in all transparent materials": "",
  "The boundary surface between two different substances": "",
  "In optics, a medium is any material or substance through which light can travel, such as air, water, glass, or a vacuum. Each medium has its own refractive index that determines how fast light moves through it.": "",
  "What is an 'optically denser' medium?": "",
  "A medium that is physically heavier than another material": "",
  "A medium that absorbs more light than it transmits through": "",
  "A medium with a higher refractive index where light is slower": "",
  "A medium that reflects all incoming light at every angle": "",
  "An optically denser medium has a higher refractive index, meaning light travels more slowly through it. For example, glass (n ≈ 1.5) is optically denser than air (n ≈ 1.0).": "",
  "What does the term 'incident ray' refer to?": "",
  "The ray that bounces off the surface after reflection occurs": "",
  "The ray of light that approaches and strikes a surface": "",
  "The ray that passes through a material after refraction": "",
  "The imaginary line drawn perpendicular to the surface": "",
  "The incident ray is the incoming ray of light that travels toward and strikes a surface. It is distinct from the reflected ray (which bounces back) and the refracted ray (which passes through).": "",
  "What is meant by 'dispersion' of light?": "",
  "The splitting of white light into different colors by a prism": "",
  "The complete absorption of light by an opaque dark surface": "",
  "The bending of light around the edges of small obstacles": "",
  "The scattering of light in all directions by rough surfaces": "",
  "Dispersion is the separation of white light into its component colors (spectrum) because different wavelengths refract by different amounts. A prism demonstrates this, producing a rainbow of colors.": "",
  "What does the 'angle of refraction' describe?": "",
  "The angle between the refracted ray and the surface boundary": "",
  "The angle between the incident ray and the refracted ray path": "",
  "The angle between the refracted ray and the normal line": "",
  "The angle between the reflected ray and the refracted ray": "",
  "The angle of refraction is the angle between the refracted ray and the normal at the point where light crosses the boundary between two media. Like the angle of incidence, it is measured from the normal.": "",
  "Define the term 'reflected ray' in optics.": "",
  "The ray that bends as it enters a new transparent medium": "",
  "The imaginary line perpendicular to the reflective surface": "",
  "The ray that bounces back from a surface into the same medium": "",
  "The reflected ray is the ray of light that bounces off a surface and returns to the original medium. According to the law of reflection, it makes the same angle with the normal as the incident ray.": "",
  "What is an 'optical boundary' between two media?": "",
